    <h1>State of Coffee Machine Maintenance 2026</h1>
    <p><em>Hygiene, Downtime, and the Case for Transparent Maintenance</em></p>
    <p>Prepared by BaristaCare ‚Ä¢ February 2026</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Executive Summary</h2>
  <p>Commercial coffee machines in caf√©s and restaurants across the U.S. and Europe face a hidden crisis: poor maintenance leads to microbial contamination, equipment downtime, and lost revenue.</p>
  <p>Despite rising demand for specialty coffee (46% of U.S. adults drink it daily, NCA 2025), only 30‚Äì40% of establishments perform regular deep cleaning. Bacteria, mold, and biofilm thrive in neglected machines ‚Äî especially in steam wands, drip trays, and water reservoirs.</p>
  <p>The cost? Up to <strong>$2,000/month in lost sales</strong> due to avoidable downtime. And even when cleaned, there‚Äôs no way for guests ‚Äî or owners ‚Äî to verify it happened.</p>
  <p>This report synthesizes data from NCA, SCA, NSF, Mordor Intelligence, and industry publications (2025‚Äì2026) to outline the real state of coffee machine hygiene ‚Äî and a practical path forward.</p>

  <h2>Key Findings</h2>

  <h3>Market Context</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Europe‚Äôs commercial coffee machine market is growing at 3.2‚Äì6.64% CAGR through 2033 (Cognitive Market Research).</li>
    <li>The U.S. and Europe account for ~60% of global automated espresso machine sales (Intel Market Research, 2026).</li>
    <li>Specialty coffee consumption is mainstream: 46% of U.S. adults drink it daily (NCA 2025).</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Maintenance Reality</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Average deep-clean interval in caf√©s: <strong>1‚Äì4 weeks</strong>.</li>
    <li>But 65%+ of professionals say it should be done <strong>weekly</strong> (Perfect Daily Grind, 2025).</li>
    <li>Only 30‚Äì40% of caf√©s perform full disassembly and sanitization regularly.</li>
  </ul>

